<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1059,378,488]" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">
D i a g n o s i s: The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Spinola" authorityYear="1844" box="[470,567,378,399]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pelonium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="1010" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[470,567,378,399]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">Pelonium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
SPINOLA was revised in 2018 (
<bibRefCitation author="OPITZ W" box="[908,1047,378,400]" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009" pagination="337 - 527" refId="ref53813" refString="OPITZ W. (2018 b): Classification, natural history, and evolution of the Subfamily Peloniinae OPITZ (Coleoptera: Cleroidea: Cleridae). Part X. Taxonomic revision of the New World genus Pelonium SPINOLA. - Entomofauna 39 (2): 337 - 527." type="journal article" year="2018">OPITZ 2018b</bibRefCitation>
). This work included a key to species groups and species. The available specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[151,364,437,458]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pelonium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="erudiatum">
<emphasis box="[151,364,437,458]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">Pelonium erudiatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
keys out to the 
<emphasis box="[554,636,437,458]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">amabile</emphasis>
group, in which it is distinguished by showing elytral asetiferous punctures that abruptly end at elytral distal 2/3 
<superScript attach="none" box="[902,915,462,476]" fontSize="6" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">rd</superScript>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1059,503,760]" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">
D e s c r i p t i o n: Size: Length 8.0 mm; width 
<quantity box="[673,753,503,525]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009" unit="mm" value="2.5">2.5 mm</quantity>
. Form: As in 
<figureCitation box="[895,980,503,525]" captionStart="Figs 334-337" captionStartId="111.[151,191,1513,1535]" captionTargetBox="[153,1058,199,1497]" captionTargetId="figure@111.[152,1058,199,1497]" captionTargetPageId="111" captionText="Figs 334-337: Habitus; (334) Pelonium implacide; (335) P. tayrona; (336) P. erudiatum; (337) Pujoliclerus abditus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746828" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746828/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">Fig. 336</figureCitation>
. Color: Forebody and pterothorax castaneous; antenna testaceous; elytra dark testaceous; legs testaceous, femora infuscated distally; abdomen dark testaceous. Head: Cranium coarsely punctate; antenna (
<figureCitation box="[347,423,591,613]" captionStart="Figs 28-42" captionStartId="71.[151,191,1299,1321]" captionTargetBox="[152,1047,199,1264]" captionTargetId="figure@71.[152,1059,199,1284]" captionTargetPageId="71" captionText="Figs 28-42: Antennae; (28) Neorthopleura thomasi, male; (29) N. thomasi, female; (30) N. subfasciata, male; (31) Artoadenus atrafinus; (32) Neorthopleura subfasciata, female; (33) Akonesis atraordinis; (34) Pelonium erudiatum; (35) Neorthopleura cuspidis, female; (36) Agnatis curvabilis; (37) Ichnea paraguayensis; (38) Neorthopleura quintana, male; (39) Pyticara frontegalba; (40) Platynoptera potaro; (41) Neorthopleura cuspidis, male; (42) Nanoclerus fuscus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746748" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746748/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">Fig. 34</figureCitation>
) capitate, funicular antennomeres shorter towards capitulum, capitular antennomeres 9 and 10 long triangular, antennomere 11 ovoid; eyes large, coarsely facetted, eye narrower than frons (EW/FW 30/44). Thorax: Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[964,1051,650,672]" captionStart="Figs 163-170" captionStartId="79.[151,191,1521,1543]" captionTargetBox="[183,1039,199,1493]" captionTargetId="figure@79.[151,1059,199,1508]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="Figs 163-170: Pronota; (163) Artoadenus atrafinus; (164) Cregya triguttula; (165) C. biguttula; (166) Perilypus schusteri (167) Platynoptera potaro; (168) Pelonium erudiatum; (169) Parapelonides aodontus; (170) Isoparis cassidilis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3746764" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3746764/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">Fig. 168</figureCitation>
) oblong (PW/PL 105/115), disc coarsely punctate, lateral tubercles well developed; elytra sculptured with 10 striae of large asetiferous punctures that abruptly end at elytral posterior 2/3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[280,293,734,748]" fontSize="6" pageId="50" pageNumber="1009">rd</superScript>
(EL/EW 350/85). Abdomen: Pygidium scutiform.
</paragraph>
